<DOC><DOCNO> AP900525-0252 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-90 2110EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-ChryslerTreasurer     05-25 0193</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Chrysler Treasurer,0201</SECOND><HEAD>Chrysler Treasurer Expected to Leave</HEAD><DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chrysler Corp. Treasurer FrederickZuckerman is likely to retire this summer to become involved inother business matters, a company spokesman said Friday.   ``Our management reluctantly agreed to let Fred pursue the manyother opportunities open to someone with his knowledge andexpertise,'' said company spokesman Tom Houston.   He said officials of the nation's No. 3 auto maker acted afterZuckermen told them several months ago of his desire ``to involvehimself in corporate restructuring.''   An exact date for Zuckerman's departure has not been set,Houston said, but likely would be this summer.   Zuckerman, 55, became Chrysler's vice president and treasurer inDecember 1981, when the company was in the throes of beating backbankruptcy on the strength of federal loan guarantees.   Recently Chrysler has fallen on hard times again and is in themidst of a cost-cutting program designed to carve $1.5 billion outof its $26 million annual budget by the end of the year.   Zuckerman joined Chrysler in October 1979 as an assistantcontroller. Before becoming vice president and treasurer, he was ageneral assistant controller.</TEXT></DOC>